node.text: Some of your favorite @TikTok creators are coming to @AirbnbExperiences. Go behind the scenes and learn their secrets of self-expression—right from home. Work out with @trevorbell, take better photos with @bonnierzm, make home videos with @itsthemcfarlands, dance with choreographer @arbengiga and more. Link in bio.

node.text: Happy Mother’s Day from Miami baker and @airbnbexperiences host, @laromibakery. Originally from Argentina, she’ll show you how to make traditional alfajores that are sure to sweeten up Mom’s day. For as beautiful as these dulce de leche sandwich cookies turn out, they’re surprisingly simple to make. Follow Romina’s foolproof recipe or join her Online Experience to make a sweet suite of Latin desserts. Link in bio.

node.text: Happy Mother’s Day from Nashville-based singer-songwriter and @airbnbexperiences host, @annebucklemusic. Follow Anne’s simple tricks for crafting a tune, or join her Online Experience for live instruction and melody-making. Link in bio.

node.text:
In March, @AirbnbExperiences hosts all over the world had to stop doing what they love—sharing their interests and passions with others. 
Over the past few weeks, they’ve offered ideas for how to continue hosting even while we’re apart. 
They’ve adapted recipes based on what’s in their pantries, turned living rooms into yoga studios, and choreographed dances for families at home.

Today we’re excited to announce that Airbnb Experiences are now online. You can take a flamenco class with Lidón in Madrid, participate in a tarot card reading with Mak in Austin, or visit a colony of penguins in Cape Town—all from home.

True to Airbnb Experiences in real life, Online Experiences are hosted by remarkable people and set in small groups. Alongside making a new dish, maybe you’ll make a new friend, too.

Thank you to our incredible hosts around the world. We’ll see you online soon —> link in bio.

node.title: Meet Homage Hospitality, the hosts who built the hotel they always wanted.

node.accessibility_caption: A wooden room with two caramel-colored sitting chairs and a coffee table in between. The one on the left has a blue throw blanket.

node.text:
Wake to mooing cows at Superhost Andy’s two-story treehouse, which hugs the trunk of an old oak in a horse pasture. When you feel like branching out, head to nearby Ruurlo Castle, a medieval estate that now houses a lively art museum.

Link in bio to sway where you stay.

Photos: @mooieplaatjesbyrt

node.accessibility_caption: A wooden room with two caramel-colored sitting chairs and a coffee table in between. The one on the left has a blue throw blanket.
A wooden treehouse with orange trim sits cocooned around an oak tree.
The bedroom inside the treehouse with caramel colored bedding and throw pillows. There is a nightstand on the right side with blue towels on top and a lamp.
The ceiling of the treehouse is adorned with plants, beams, and hanging light bulbs.
A hammock hangs inside the treehouse with a large branch exposed and a telescope points out the window.
The first floor kitchenette dining counter looks out to a green grassy yard. There are two barstools and two blue plates with two glasses of orange juice.
Photo by Airbnb in Fairfax, California. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text:
Superhost MaryBeth made her tiny house a revitalizing solo sanctuary. Guests love how alive with nature it feels—one noted “hummingbirds coming so close I could feel the vibration of their wings.” Just don’t get so blissed out that you forget to walk into town for a vanilla honey lavender cone from Fairfax Scoop. 

Link in bio for Marin refuge.

Photo: @coleypagan

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb on September 09, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
Find peace among the pines at Superhost Dominique’s elegant retreat. After breakfast on your balcony, explore the cobblestone-lined town (Dominique has plenty of local tips) or set sail on Lake Avándaro. 

Link in bio for forest suite.

Photos: @andieac

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb on September 09, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.
Photo by Airbnb on September 09, 2021. May be an image of furniture, tree and indoor.
Photo by Airbnb on September 09, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.
Photo by Airbnb on September 09, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

A blue two story treehouse sits on stilts amongst the trees. It is surrounded by green grass and plants on the ground, with two patio chairs. To the left there is also a lookout deck at the level of the treehouse.

node.text:
Guests praise every detail of Superhost Susan’s luxury treehouse, from the tilework to the vintage jukebox (bowl of quarters included). They also love her local recommendations, like Mauricio’s for Italian classics and Ralph’s for fresh donuts and apple fritters.

Link in bio for Upper Cumberland home base.

Photo: @sulfurridge

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb on September 08, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
Disappear into the jungle at Superhost Mikheyla’s secluded treehouse. If you can ever break the cycle of soaking in your hot tub and plunging into the cool river that runs right under your balcony, climb Mount Manunggal for a broader view of this lush island. 

Link in bio for Cebu sanctuary.

Photos: @mikheylafox

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb on September 08, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.
Photo by Airbnb on September 08, 2021.
Photo by Airbnb on September 08, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.
A large window showcases a sunset view of the Pollença Bay. Two white chairs and a round glass coffee table sit in front of the window against the white wall.

node.text:
Superhost Joan’s house on the Bay of Pollença puts you a short walk from several beaches and the historic walled town. In the unlikely event that it doesn’t satisfy your appetite for majestic views, take the winding drive up to the clifftop Cap de Formentor lighthouse. 

Link in bio for Mallorca magic.

Photo: @wander_lozz

node.text:
This bamboo villa might just make you rethink the whole indoor bathing fad. It’s surrounded by rice fields but only a five-minute bike ride from the heart of town, where you can start your afternoon with tea by the lotus pond just outside the Saraswati temple. 

Link in bio for serene shower.

Video: @dbytang

node.accessibility_caption: A bedroom in neutral tones, with wood beamed ceilings, a hammock in the right corner, next to a wooden door. Besides the door is a wooden chest of four drawers and a floor mirror with the bed with a white comforter and great blanket to the left of the photo.

node.text:
137 years old and more handsome than ever. Superhost Michelle and family transformed this 19th century creekside cabin into a cozy retreat. She’ll point you toward her favorite High Country adventures, too, possibly including the natural waterslide hidden nearby. 

Link in bio for Sugar Mountain sweetness.

Photo: @this.old.river.cabin

node.text:
Join Elizabeth for a healing session among the red rocks of Sedona. An artist with Chippewa, Sioux, and English ancestry, she draws from many spiritual traditions—and from the area’s serene landscape. Elizabeth will guide you through a medicine wheel process designed to relieve you of long-carried burdens and provide a new perspective.

Link in bio to get inspired.

node.accessibility_caption: A bedroom with dark blue bedding surrounded by hanging plants from the cieling.

node.text:
Superhost Jessica made her backyard cabin as lively and charming as the walkable Foster-Powell neighborhood that surrounds it. Fuel up first at the Portland Mercado, where the Latin American food carts range from Argentinian to Oaxacan.

Link in bio to avoid FoPo FOMO.

Photo: @sidneyscottmusic
Stay: @fostercabin

node.accessibility_caption:
A detailed image of the red beams with colorful painted arrows and swirled designs against a bright blue sky with the
sun shining in the right corner.

node.text:
A ceiling like this deserves to be stared at by as many people as possible. That’s why Superhost Fabienne designed her Mongolian-inspired yurt with accessibility in mind. She’ll also share all her favorite storybook villages and other day-trip destinations. 

Link in bio for accessible Alsace.

node.accessibility_caption:
A detailed image of the red beams with colorful painted arrows and swirled designs against a bright blue sky with the
sun shining in the right corner.
Inside a yurt with red wood beams, a bed with black comforter and tan canvas walls.

An up close shot of the support beams of the yurt which are a red base color with green, blue, and white swirled
designs.

Inside a converted barn with vaulted ceilings with wooden beams. The charming rustic furniture includes a red couch, yellow armchair, and coffee table to the left of the photo. While towards the right, there is a long kitchen table with a bench on one side and chairs on the other. It is surrounded by cream walls with vertical wood accents.

node.text:
It may be almost half a millennium old, but this barn has been so charmingly converted that guests tend to spend part of their stay planning a return visit. It also doesn’t hurt that Superhosts Michelle and Michael are as generous with their local knowledge as they are with homemade treats. When you’re ready to explore, start by walking into town for a ploughman’s lunch at the Bent Arms. 

Link in bio for East Sussex countryside.

Photo: @thegranarybarn
